<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus torreyana </i>is a slow-growing pine that attains an age of about 150 years. It is the rarest pine in North America, occurring as disjunct populations on the mainland and on an island off southern California. Three populations exist, with about 9,000 trees. The two subspecies of <i>P. torreyana </i>differ in needle and cone characters (Haller 1967). Both subspecies are rare CNPS list 1B plants (CNPS 2001). The species grows with coastal scrub and chaparral alliances. Local endemics include CNPS list 1B plants <i>Arctostaphylos glandulosa </i>ssp. <i>crassifolia, Baccharis vanessae, </i>and <i>Quercus dumosa, </i>and CNPS list 2 plants <i>Coreopsis maritima </i>and <i>Ceanothus verrucosus</i>. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pinus torreyana </i> is adapted to a harsh environment of nutrient-poor soils, low winter rainfall, and frequent fog in a maritime climate.  The alliance is localized, occurring along coastal bluffs associated with maritime chaparral and coastal scrub on both Santa Rosa Island and the mainland in northern San Diego Co. This vegetation type has been upgraded to a full alliance from "Special Stands," as it was cited originally in <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>  (2009) and in Sproul et al. (2011), subsequent to classification analyses of surveys in the northern Channel Islands (Rodriguez et al. 2017). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
