    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bc, Bj). The larger mainland population and stands of <i>Pinus torreyana</i> ssp. <i>torreyana</i> occur in the vicinity of Del Mar and Torrey Pines State Reserve in San Diego Co. (Holland 1986); two island populations and stands of ssp. <i>insularis</i> occur on Santa Rosa Island in Santa Barbara Co. (Clark et al. 1990, Rodriguez et al. 2017). CVIS (1995) has vegetation plot data on file for Torrey Pines State Park in San Diego Co., and Evens and San (2006) and Sproul et al. (2011) sampled the nearby localized stands in the Del Mar region of that county; these stands are identified as <i>Pinus torreyana / Artemisia californica - Rhus integrifolia</i> association.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus torreyana </i> has little capacity to respond to change through natural selection because of low genetic variability. Native populations need management to maintain a maximum number of trees while minimizing the chance of catastrophic loss (Ledig 1984). If fires occur in a Torrey pine stand at intervals shorter than 12 to 18 years, (when saplings begin to produce cones), they could seriously impair the ability of the population to survive. 

This pine (as well as other coastal and interior conifers) has delayed seed dispersal after fire and reduced serotiny, which likely has arisen from a fire pattern in which large scale, intense crown fires have alternated with long intervals of no fires or of only low-severity surface fires (McMaster 1980). Seed dispersal has been studied by McMaster and Zedler (1981) and Johnson et al. (2003).

Both the island and mainland stands are threatened by air pollution, since the densely populated areas of southern California generate extreme amounts of air pollution which is carried by Santa Ana winds to the coast and offshore islands (Little 1975, Davis 1989). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
